Anti-Synergy and Guardrail Rules
1. Never allow the same kill event to recursively trigger unlimited kill events.
2. On-hit amplification and damage-over-time amplification must declare whether they stack multiplicatively or not.
3. Dual-area denial props must share visual priority rules so the floor never becomes unreadable.
4. Economy props may improve stability, but may not delete the intended risk of debt, bandits, or greedy holds.
5. Summon-count props must convert excess quantity into quality before performance collapses.

A15. Boss Modifier Policy and Performance Safety Rules
This section defines how prop effects should be reduced, capped, or reformatted in boss encounters and high-density late-wave situations.

Boss Modifier Policy
| effect_family | default boss treatment | reason |
| --- | --- | --- |
| splash_damage | 40% to 60% effectiveness unless explicitly exempt | prevents wave-clear tools from becoming free boss delete buttons |
| damage_over_time | reduced tick value or capped stack count | keeps DoT relevant without replacing mechanical execution |
| hard_control | duration reduction or control immunity windows | bosses must remain readable and interactive |
| coin_economy | no direct boss payout inflation beyond explicit reward rules | prevents boss farming exploits |
| reflect_damage | capped by boss-facing multiplier or trigger cooldown | avoids passive kill loops |
| summon_pressure | maintain uptime target, but reduce AI abuse around boss hazards | preserves path identity without cheese |

Late-Wave Performance Safety Rules
1. Any prop that spawns secondary projectiles must define a hard concurrent cap.
2. Any trail or puddle system must define both a lifetime and maximum active count.
3. Any chain effect must define max jumps, retarget filters, and duplicate-target lockout.
4. Any periodic scan aura must define scan interval and maximum affected targets per tick.
5. Any visually persistent floor effect must define z-order priority and fade behavior.

Recommended Runtime Safety Checklist
| system_type | required safety control | example |
| --- | --- | --- |
| projectile burst | max active secondary projectiles | shrapnel_shells, shardstorm |
| chain logic | unique target list per trigger | shock_relay |
| area decals | max active instances plus pooled cleanup | sticky_tar_flask, curing_paint |
| pulse/aura | fixed tick interval and target cap | time_dilation_boots, aegis_pulse |
| summon counts | soft cap with quality conversion | auto_turret, stationary_turret, future summoner props |

Boss Design Compatibility Rules
1. Every prop family should still matter in boss fights, but not at full trash-wave value.
2. Boss nerfs must be surfaced in tooltip or inspect copy when the difference is material.
3. If a prop is weak on bosses by design, it must be strong enough on waves to justify the slot.
4. No boss should fully invalidate an entire path unless that path has alternative payoff elsewhere in the run.

