37. Prop Presentation Standard (Per Card, Per Upgrade)
37.1. Required card data fields (display-facing)
Every prop must expose the following display-facing fields:
display_name
path_tag
role_tag
rarity
short_pitch
current_value_text
next_upgrade_text
synergy_tags
risk_note (if the prop has a drawback or tradeoff)

37.2. Naming rules
Names should be short, distinct, and scannable in under 1 second.
Target length guideline:
1-3 words preferred, 18 characters soft cap before text scaling.
Avoid generic names that overlap in function:
Bad example:
Power Boost, Damage Up, Strong Shot.
Good example:
Retaliation Core, Grave Beacon, Razor Loop.

37.3. Short pitch format
The short pitch is the primary purchase-value sentence and must describe outcome, not only math.
Examples:
Spawn an extra frontliner that draws enemy aggro.
Turn crit chains into room-clearing burst windows.
Convert painted ground into safe damage zones.
Pitch length target:
45-70 characters.

37.4. Upgrade preview standard
All upgrade previews must show the absolute delta and the new total.
Preferred format:
Damage: +8 (32 -> 40)
Cooldown: -0.3s (2.1s -> 1.8s)
Summon Cap: +1 (3 -> 4)
Never show only a percentage if the player can understand the concrete number instead.

37.5. Synergy tag rules
Each prop should display 2-4 synergy tags at most.
Tag priority order:
Primary path -> trigger type -> scaling stat -> notable combo.
Example:
SUMMONER | On Kill | Attack Speed | Swarm

38. Shop Anti-Frustration and Offer Quality Rules
38.1. Offer quality baseline
Each shop refresh should contain:
At least 1 generally safe pick.
At least 1 synergy-forward pick tied to current build if available.
At least 1 wildcard pick with high upside or pivot potential.

38.2. Dead shop prevention
Do not allow three consecutive shops with zero path matches once the player has committed to a path.
If the player owns 3+ props from a single path, increase that path's appearance weight by a controlled amount only:
Recommended range:
+12% to +20%, not uncapped.

38.3. Anti-duplicate frustration
Do not offer duplicate maxed-out props.
Do not offer the same rejected prop more than twice in three shops unless the item pool is near exhaustion.
If a prop was rerolled away, reduce its immediate reappearance chance for one shop cycle.

38.4. Pivot protection
Even in a heavily committed build, keep 10-20% of offers open for pivot or rescue options.
Purpose:
Prevent runs from becoming solved too early.
Preserve comeback routes after bad boss matchups.

38.5. Price feel targets
Cheap buy should feel instantly attainable.
Mid-cost buy should feel like a meaningful choice.
High-cost buy should feel aspirational, not impossible.
If a player cannot afford any item in two consecutive shops during an average run, economy pacing is failing.

39. Run Summary, Loss Screen, and Build Clarity
39.1. End-run summary minimum content
Required fields:
Primary path
Secondary path
Top 5 props by impact
Peak DPS
Total summons created
Coins spent vs coins earned
Bosses defeated
Cause of death or victory condition

39.2. Build identity callout
Generate a readable build label from actual run behavior.
Examples:
Swarm Commander
Crit Cascade
Paint Lock Controller
Greedy Merchant Tank
This improves memorability and shareability.

39.3. Loss analysis suggestions
Loss tips must be evidence-based.
Use actual run signals:
Low mobility uptime
Low single-target boss damage
Too many economy props too early
Insufficient survivability for elite spikes
Avoid generic advice like:
Try a better build.

39.4. Personal best and progression messaging
Always surface new personal records when they occur.
Best practice:
One prominent stat card + up to two secondary record callouts.
Do not flood the summary screen with too many celebration banners.

40. Content Pacing and Run Variety Requirements
40.1. Early game (minutes 0-5)
Player should learn:
Core movement safety
One strong prop identity
One upgrade rhythm
The early game must be forgiving without feeling flat.
Target:
One exciting power spike before minute 4.

40.2. Mid game (minutes 5-15)
The run should begin forcing specialization.
Enemies should force tradeoff recognition:
Single-target vs crowd clear
Greed vs survival
Static control vs mobility
At least one enemy type or event should pressure over-optimized glass-cannon builds.

40.3. Late game (minutes 15+ or equivalent final stages)
The build should feel fully online, but still threatened.
Late-game threats should test:
Position discipline
Burst survival
Boss mechanic understanding
Not just raw stat checks.

40.4. Variety injection system
Run variety should come from:
Enemy composition shifts
Boss modifier variants
Event room choices
Path-specific prop forks
Randomness alone is insufficient; controlled variation is preferable to chaos.

41. Production Polish Requirements (Mature Release Standard)
41.1. Animation polish
All major card interactions must share one clear motion language:
Appear, hover, buy, fail-to-buy, upgrade.
Animation durations must be short and reliable:
Recommended UI motion range:
100-220ms.
Longer timings make repeated shop interactions feel sluggish.

41.2. Audio polish
There must be separate layers for:
UI feedback
Player proc confirmation
Enemy telegraphs
Boss phase transitions
If two sounds compete for the same gameplay meaning, redesign one.

41.3. Micro-feedback standards
Every successful purchase must produce:
Visual confirmation
Audio confirmation
State update confirmation (coin count and item state)
Every failed purchase must produce:
Short denied audio + red pulse + readable reason if relevant.

41.4. Low-end device fallback
Provide a reduced-VFX mode:
Lower particle count
Reduced bloom/glow
Simplified paint overlay
Lower summon trail density
This mode must preserve gameplay clarity, not merely reduce visual quality.

41.5. Final release polish gate
Before broader public release, verify:
No placeholder text
No inconsistent capitalization in tooltips
No missing icon assets
No props with undocumented hidden effects
No path colors that differ between shop, tooltip, and summary UI

